  "prompt_text": "What is the time complexity of merge sort and why? Walk through the recurrence relation.",
  "response_text": "The time complexity of merge sort is O(n log n), where n is the number of elements in the array being sorted. This is because merge sort is a divide-and-conquer algorithm that splits the array into two halves until each subarray contains only one element, and then merges the subarrays back together in sorted order.\n\nHere's a step-by-step breakdown of the recurrence relation:\n\n1.  **Base case**: If the array has only one element, it is already sorted, so the time complexity is O(1).\n2.  **Divide**: If the array has more than one element, we split it into two halves, each containing n/2 elements.\n3.  **Conquer**: We recursively apply the merge sort algorithm to each half of the array, resulting in two sorted subarrays.\n4.  **Combine**: We merge the two sorted subarrays back together to form a single sorted array.\n\nThe recurrence relation for merge sort can be expressed as:\n\nT(n) = 2T(n/2) + O(n)\n\nHere's why this recurrence relation holds:\n\n*   The 2T(n/2) term represents the time complexity of recursively sorting the two halves of the array.\n*   The O(n) term represents the time complexity of merging the two sorted subarrays back together.\n\nTo solve this recurrence relation, we can use the Master Theorem, which states that if a recurrence relation has the form T(n) = aT(n/b) + f(n), where a ≥ 1, b > 1, and f(n) is a function of n, then the solution is:\n\nT(n) = O(n^(log_b(a)) \\* f(n)^(log_b(a) / (log_b(a) - 1))\n\nIn this case, a = 2, b = 2, and f(n) = O(n). Plugging these values into the Master Theorem, we get:\n\nT(n) = O(n^(log_2(2)) \\* (O(n))^(log_2(2) / (log_2(2) - 1))\nT(n) = O(n^1 \\* O(n)^(1 / (1 - 1)))\nT(n) = O(n^1 \\* O(n)^(∞))\nT(n) = O(n^1 \\* ∞)\nT(n) = O(n^1 \\* ∞) = O(n log n)\n\nTherefore, the time complexity of merge sort is O(n log n).\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 6\nF (Flex",
